      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to explain. In your student loan amortization schedule, your monthly payment is divided into two parts: the interest portion and the principal repayment portion. The interest portion is calculated based on the remaining principal balance at the beginning of the month. As you continue to make payments, the interest portion decreases while the principal portion increases. However, the interest is calculated on the remaining balance, which can still be a significant amount if the loan has a long term or a high interest rate. This is why you may feel like your money is disappearing, as a large part of your payment goes towards interest rather than reducing the principal balance. Over time, as the principal balance decreases, the interest portion of the payment will also decrease, allowing more of your payment to go towards repaying the principal.",
